Float switches on the suction vessels alarm when a high level is reached.  If the liquid level continues to rise, additional float switches and/or level control shut off the appropriate compressors or boosters to avoid slugging.
To adjust for changing refrigeration loads, system pressures (compressor operation) are controlled by a step controller for the manufacturing system and a programmable logic controller for the mezzanine system.  These controls include delay timers to prevent short cycling (frequent start-up/shutdown/start-up) of the compressors and boosters.  In addition, the cooling towers include a system which automatically supplies city water in the event of water pump failure (to prevent a sudden increase in the high-side discharge pressure).
A release of ammonia that could affect the environment is unlikely for the following reasons:
A? Many of the high pressure liquid lines are located in enclosed areas that could help to contain such a release, and the outside piping is elevated to promote dispersion;
A? Industrial standards were followed for the manufacture and quality control of these lines;
A? Ammonia is not corrosive in this service;
A? Most of the lines are elevated to minimize potential damage from fork lifts;
A? The facility has a preventive maintenance program in place to maintain the ongoing integrity of the system;
A? The facility has a training program designed to ensure that the system is operated by qualified personnel; and
A? The facility has emergency response procedures which enable trained personnel to respond quickly to isolate any potential releases by closing valves in the liquid lines.

